    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-07-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-07-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="569"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d569">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">550.S1/117</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Chargé (<persName corresp="#p_OFDG1" type="from"
                            >Osborne</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 238</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-28">July 28,
                            1932</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honour under instructions from His
                    Majesty’s Principal Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs to transmit to you
                    herewith two notes on the subject of the World Economic Conference.<note n="11"
                        xml:id="d569fn11">For texts of notes, see Department of State, <hi
                            rend="italic">Press Releases</hi>, July 30, 1932, pp. 82–83.</note>
                    These notes invite the United States Government to be represented on the
                    Committee of the Council of the League of Nations which is charged with the task
                    of convoking the Conference and to <pb facs="0939" n="819" xml:id="pg_819"/>
                    appoint two experts to sit on the Committee charged with the preliminary
                    examination of the financial and economic questions referred to in Resolution
                        V.<note n="12" xml:id="d569fn12">For text, see Great Britain, Cmd. No. 4126,
                        Misc. No. 7 (1932); see also Department of State, <hi rend="italic">Press
                            Releases</hi>, July 30, 1932, pp. 83–84.</note> attached to the Final
                    Act of the Lausanne Conference.</p>
                <p>I have further the honour to inform you that these invitations are extended on
                    the understanding that the questions of Reparations, of Debts and of specific
                    tariff rates (as distinguished from tariff policy) will be excluded from the
                    scope of the Conference and that among the monetary matters within its scope
                    will be the question of silver.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_OFDG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">D. G. Osborne</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
